SIMPLE: hostility
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hostility
<hw>Hos*til"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Hostilities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>hostilitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>hostilit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>State of being hostile; public or private enemy;
unfriendliness; animosity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hostility</qex> being thus suspended with France.</q>
<rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An act of an open enemy; a hostile deed; especially
in the plural, acts of warfare; attacks of an enemy. See
<er>hostilities</er></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He who proceeds to wanton <qex>hostility</qex>, often provokes an
enemy where he might have a friend.</q> <rj><qau>Crabb.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Animosity; enmity; opposition; violence;
aggression; contention; warfare.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hostilize</ent>⟦br⟧
